An integrated theory of ageing in the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

Gems D(1).

Author information:
(1)Department of Biology, University College London, UK. dgems@galton.ucl.ac.uk

Numerous theories of ageing have been proposed, and many have been tested 
experimentally, particularly using nematode models such as Caenorhabditis 
elegans. By combining those theories of ageing that remain plausible with recent 
findings from studies of C. elegans life span mutants, an integrated theory of 
ageing has been devised. This is formed from 3 interconnected elements: the 
evolutionary theory of ageing, the oxidative damage theory of ageing, and a 
nonadaptive programmed ageing theory. This tripartite theory of ageing gives 
rise to a number of predictions that may be tested experimentally.

